{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/lung-pleural-cancers-recognition-referral/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f842e0db-8d8c-5498-b118-9eb5f444f84d","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 50119c19-7c09-4b52-8b52-d402c490b3dc --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 50119c19-7c09-4b52-8b52-d402c490b3dc -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b57b99ec-ac2a-4980-aaef-147b52d4155f --><!-- begin field 4b1a55d2-afea-4d4a-9b78-e4c0745018bd --><ul><li><strong>Over 43,000 new lung cancers </strong><strong>are diagnosed each year in the UK.</strong></li><li>A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately one person with lung cancer each year.</li><li>Lung cancer is seen in both sexes. Historically, it was much more common in males, though 45% of new diagnoses are now in females.</li><li><strong>Over 2500 new mesotheliomas are diagnosed each year in the UK,</strong> though the incidence is increasing rapidly. Most are pleural, though peritoneal mesotheliomas also occur.</li><li>A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately 2â€“3 people with mesothelioma in their career.</li><li>Mesothelioma is seen in both sexes, though currently 85% of new mesotheliomas occur in males.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/lung-pleural-cancers-recognition-referral/references/\">National Collaborating Centre for Cancer, 2015</a>]</p><!-- end field 4b1a55d2-afea-4d4a-9b78-e4c0745018bd --><!-- end item b57b99ec-ac2a-4980-aaef-147b52d4155f -->","topic":{"id":"7d8c9378-296e-5faf-9c97-f97a7697364d","topicId":"2a330e0f-ed6b-480c-bb50-2b5e80aec564","topicName":"Lung and pleural cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"lung-pleural-cancers-recognition-referral","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2021","chapters":[{"id":"9ea3734a-4640-5249-855d-86a7092ebddf","fullIte